text.tspan: Point-to-Point, infinite acceleration.
Theoretically the position error is small
and the speed error is small. However:
no mechanical system can have infinite
acceleration. "Almost" infinite acceleration
requires the speed to be low, for the system
to follow the movement.
Point-to-Point with acceleration.
Accelerate and decelerate
on the curve vectors. Position error
is small, speed error is large. You may
need to modulate the laser power to
prevent burning the corners or widening
the lines.
fly-over. Accelerate and decelerate
before and after the curve points.
Position error is small, speed error is small.
Requires more time. In precise laser timing
may cause small gaps or over cuts in the
corners (depending on speed and timing
accuracy)
Sloppy marking. Approximate the
sharp corners by deceleration one axis
and accelerating the other at the same
time. Position error is large, speed error
is smaller. Can be used for curved shapes
that do not require exact tolerances.
Shorter marking time compared to other
options.
